Obesity and Education Background

We are interested in examining a relationship between obesity and educational level.

The education data set in the file education.csv summarizes education level in Wisconsin by zip code and sex with the percentage of men and women age 25 and older who have a bachelor’s degree or higher. There is one row per zip code and separate columns for females and males with a small amount of missing data.

The obesity data is broken down more finely: we have one row for each zip code, sex, and age range.

In order to join these data sets, we will want to reshape each so that there is one row per zip code and sex. The reshaped education data set will have columns zip, sex, and pct_bachelors with the percentage of individuals aged 25 and older of the given sex in that zip code with at least a bachelors degree. The reshaped obesity data set will have columns zip, sex and pct_obese with the estimated population percentage of adult individuals in the given sex and zip code that are obese (BMI > 30). We will only estimate these percentages in zip codes with no missing data among adults.

Note that our adult educational variable and adult obesity variables are calculated on different subsets of the adult populations within each zip code and sex (25+ for education, 18+ for obesity). This is okay as our comparisons are at the zip code level and not the individual person level.

The first few problems involve exploring and reshaping the individual data sets. Later problems ask you to do some data analysis with these reshaped and/or joined data sets.

n is: The total number of zip codes/measurements

p_1 is: The percentage of zip codes where more there is a higher percentage of females with bachelors degrees than males

p_2 is: The percentage of zip codes where the percentage of females with bachelors degrees and males with bachelors degrees are equal

3a. Create a data frame named education in long format with a single row for each zip code and sex combination (so, two rows per zip code, one for females and one for males) using the pivot_longer() function. Prior to pivoting, drop rows with any missing data. Arrange the rows of the data set by zip code and sex. After the transformation, you should have the following columns:

  • zip = zip code; change its type to character

  • sex = sex; make the values "female" and "male"

  • pct_bachelors = % adults (aged 25+, of the given sex by zip) with at least a bachelors degree.

    3 (cont).

This data transformation will require reshaping data, changing data values, and transforming column names. There are (at least) two ways to think about doing this:

  • rename() the columns before reshaping.
  • recode() the values after reshaping.

Pick one and do it.

education = education_orig %>%
  mutate(zip = as.character(zip)) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  rename(male = pct_m_bach, female = pct_f_bach) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(male, female), names_to = "sex", values_to = "pct_bachelors") %>%
  arrange(zip, sex)

  1. Read in the obesity data set from the file obesity.csv.

  • Convert zip to be character type.

  • As in the lecture notes, add columns obese_pop and non_obese_pop which contain estimates of the number of obese individuals within the population by each row (each zip/sex/age combination).

  • Create a summary of the data named adult_pop_sum with one row for each zip code and sex combination with a variable total_pop which contains the total population of all adult men and women for each zip code (age 18 and older).

  • Display this data with side-by-side box-plots of the data with the total population for each zip code on the x axis and sex on the y axis, adding appropriate axis labels and a title.

obesity_orig = read_csv("../../data/obesity.csv") 

obesity = obesity_orig %>%
  mutate(zip = as.character(zip)) %>%
  group_by(zip, sex, age) %>%
  mutate(obese_pop = pop * (obese/n),
         non_obese_pop = pop * (1 - obese/n))

adult_pop_sum = obesity %>%
  select(zip, sex, age, pop) %>%
  filter(age >= "18") %>%
  group_by(zip, sex) %>%
  summarize(total_pop = sum(pop))
  
ggplot(adult_pop_sum, aes(x = total_pop, y = sex, color = sex)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("Total Population") + 
  ylab("Sex") +
  ggtitle("Total Population Spread by Sex")

  1. Use the newly joined education data set to estimate the percentage of women and men in the state with at least a bachelors degree. Report these percentages. (Note: You will want to determine the number of individuals for each zip code and sex with a bachelors degree before summing to get totals by sex for the whole state. You may ignore the detail that population totals are age 18+ and education level is for age 25+. You also should delete zip codes with missing education data prior to summing over zip codes for this calculation, but do not delete these rows from the education data set. Ensure that the zip variable is type character in both data sets before joining them. In addition, when using group_by() with multiple variables, all variables but the last are retained as grouping variables after summarize(). You may need to pipe a data set through ungroup() to eliminate residual grouping on occasion.)
bachelor_pcts = education %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(num_bachelors = (pct_bachelors * total_pop)/100) %>%
  group_by(sex) %>%
  summarize(pop = sum(total_pop), bachelors = sum(num_bachelors), 
            pct_bachelors = (bachelors/pop) * 100) %>% 
  print()

  1. Create a summary of the obesity data named adult_obesity_sum which contains one row for each zip code and sex with counts of the number of obese individuals (obese_pop) and the total population (total_pop) of adults age 18+ by zip code and sex. Only include zip codes with no missing data for all eight adult age groups.

  • Specifically, filter out the rows with ages 5-17, filter out rows with any missing obesity data, add a variable which counts the number of remaining rows for each zip code, and filter out rows where this count is less than 8. Once you have completed filtering out zip codes that do not have complete obesity data for all adult age groups, then, you may sum the total number of obese individuals and the total population for each remaining zip code.

  • If you have done this correctly, there are 306 zip codes with complete adult obesity data, so your obesity data set has \(306 \times 2 = 612\) rows.

  • Print the first ten rows of this data set.

adult_obesity_sum = obesity %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(age >= "18") %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  group_by(zip) %>%
  mutate(zip_num = n()) %>%
  filter(zip_num == 8) %>%
  group_by(zip, sex) %>%
  summarize(obese_pop = sum(obese_pop), total_pop = sum(pop)) %>%
  print(n = 10)

  1. Join the adult_obesity_sum and the education data sets, joining by zip code and sex, keeping only zip code / sex combinations found in both data sets. (Use by = c("zip", "sex") to specify more than one joining variable.) Add a variable pct_obese which contains the percentage of obese individuals per zip code/sex.
  • Using this data set, create a scatter plot with the obesity percentage on the y-axis versus the education percentage on the x axis. Use different colors for each sex and add a smooth curve for each sex. Describe the pattern you see: how does obesity rate change among men and women as education percentage increases?
obesity_education = inner_join(education, adult_obesity_sum, 
                               by = c("zip", "sex", "total_pop")) %>%
  mutate(pct_obese = (obese_pop / total_pop) * 100)

ggplot(obesity_education, aes(x = pct_bachelors, y = pct_obese, color = sex)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  xlab("Education") +
  ylab("Obesity") +
  ggtitle("Education Vs. Obesity in Wisconsin")

There is a strong negative linear relationship between obesity and education, meaning as education percentaes increase, obesity percentages increase. Male and females follow similar trends, however as education increases is becomes less likely that a female would be obese compared to a male.
